==Natural genetic transformation==

[[Transformation (genetics)|Natural genetic transformation]] has been reported in at least three Rhizobiales species: ''[[Agrobacterium tumefaciens]]'',<ref name="pmid11375171">{{cite journal |vauthors=Demanèche S, Kay E, Gourbière F, Simonet P |title=Natural transformation of ''Pseudomonas fluorescens'' and ''Agrobacterium tumefaciens'' in soil |journal=Appl. Environ. Microbiol. |volume=67 |issue=6 |pages=2617–21 |year=2001 |pmid=11375171 |pmc=92915 |doi=10.1128/AEM.67.6.2617-2621.2001 |url=}}</ref> ''[[Methylobacterium organophilum]]'',<ref name="pmid401866">{{cite journal |vauthors=O'Connor M, Wopat A, Hanson RS |title=Genetic transformation in ''Methylobacterium organophilum'' |journal=J. Gen. Microbiol. |volume=98 |issue=1 |pages=265–72 |year=1977 |pmid=401866 |doi=10.1099/00221287-98-1-265 |url=}}</ref> and ''[[Bradyrhizobium japonicum]]''.<ref name="pmid4538250">{{cite journal |vauthors=Raina JL, Modi VV |title=Deoxyribonucleate binding and transformation in ''Rhizobium japonicum'' |journal=J. Bacteriol. |volume=111 |issue=2 |pages=356–60 |year=1972 |pmid=4538250 |pmc=251290 |doi= |url=}}</ref>  Natural genetic transformation is a sexual process involving DNA transfer from one bacterial cell to another through the intervening medium, and the integration of the donor sequence into the recipient genome by [[homologous recombination]].

